## How They All Fit Into the Cluster

```
My cluster
│
├── kube-system namespace
│     ├── metrics-server        ← feeds kubectl top nodes/pods
│     ├── cilium (x3)           ← pod networking
│     ├── coredns (x2)          ← DNS inside the cluster
│     └── kube-proxy (x3)       ← network routing per node
│
├── monitoring namespace
│     ├── prometheus            ← scrapes metrics every 30s
│     ├── grafana               ← draws charts from prometheus
│     ├── alertmanager          ← sends alerts when things break
│     ├── kube-state-metrics    ← watches K8s objects (pods, deployments)
│     └── node-exporter (x3)   ← one per node, collects OS stats
│
├── kubernetes-dashboard namespace
│     ├── dashboard-web         ← the UI you see in the browser
│     ├── dashboard-api         ← serves data to the UI
│     ├── dashboard-auth        ← handles login tokens
│     └── dashboard-kong        ← API gateway layer
│
└── default namespace
      └── nginx (x2)            ← the test deployment
```

Node exporter runs on every single node and collects things like CPU usage, disk I/O, memory, and network traffic at the OS level. Kube-state-metrics watches the Kubernetes API and reports on things like how many pods are running versus how many should be running. Both feed into Prometheus, which Grafana then queries to draw the dashboards.

