## Install Prometheus + Grafana

Both are installed together via the `kube-prometheus-stack` Helm chart — this is the standard way to do it and it sets up everything including the pre-built Grafana dashboards automatically.

```bash
helm repo add prometheus-community https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update

helm install prometheus prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack \
  --namespace monitoring \
  --create-namespace
```

Verify everything came up:

```bash
kubectl get pods -n monitoring
# You should see: prometheus, grafana, alertmanager,
# kube-state-metrics, and node-exporter (one per node)
```

### Expose Grafana

```bash
kubectl patch svc prometheus-grafana -n monitoring \
  --type='json' \
  -p='[{"op":"replace","path":"/spec/type","value":"NodePort"}]'

kubectl get svc prometheus-grafana -n monitoring
# Note the NodePort assigned
```

Get your login credentials:

```bash
# Username
kubectl get secret -n monitoring prometheus-grafana \
  -o jsonpath="{.data.admin-user}" | base64 -d

# Password
kubectl get secret -n monitoring prometheus-grafana \
  -o jsonpath="{.data.admin-password}" | base64 -d
```

Open Grafana:

```
http://<ANY_NODE_IP>:<GRAFANA_PORT>
```

Change the password once you're in — Profile → Change Password.

### Expose Prometheus (optional — useful for querying directly)

```bash
kubectl patch svc prometheus-kube-prometheus-prometheus -n monitoring \
  --type='json' \
  -p='[{"op":"replace","path":"/spec/type","value":"NodePort"}]'

kubectl get svc prometheus-kube-prometheus-prometheus -n monitoring
```

Open Prometheus:

```
http://<ANY_NODE_IP>:<PROMETHEUS_PORT>
```

